---
import Layout from "@/layouts/Layout.astro";
import Nav from "@/components/Nav.astro";
import Footer from "@/components/Footer.astro";

const navLinks = [
  { href: "/", label: "Phidea" },
  { href: "/#archive", label: "Topics" },
  { href: "/#subscribe", label: "Subscribe" },
];
const navCta = { href: "#subscribe", label: "Subscribe →" };
---

<Layout variant="ai-visibility">
  <Nav variant="ai-visibility" links={navLinks} cta={navCta} />

  <article class="article">
    <header class="article-head">
      <div class="wrap wrap-article">
        <div class="article-meta">
          <span>Topic 01 · Distribution</span>
          <span>Reference page</span>
        </div>
        <h1>When a carrier isn't cited by ChatGPT.</h1>
        <p class="standfirst">
          Your Google rank and your ChatGPT citation rate are not the same number. This page is the starting reference.
        </p>
      </div>
    </header>

    <section class="article-body">
      <div class="wrap wrap-article">
        <p>
          AI assistants like ChatGPT, Claude, Gemini, and Perplexity answer insurance questions every day. "Am I covered for X." "Cheapest car insurance." "What does an umbrella policy do." The assistants compose a sentence, and that sentence sometimes names a specific carrier, sometimes names a competitor, and sometimes names no one at all.
        </p>

        <p>
          Whether your carrier gets named depends on what each model has read. Every assistant uses its own mix of pre-training data and live web retrieval. The full mix is not published. What is published, and what you can verify today, is how the crawlers that feed those models identify themselves, and the fact that they respect your <code>robots.txt</code>.
        </p>

        <h2>What you can verify this afternoon.</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>One, your robots.txt.</strong> Visit <code>https://your-site.com/robots.txt</code>. Look for directives involving <code>GPTBot</code>, <code>ChatGPT-User</code> and <code>OAI-SearchBot</code> (OpenAI), <code>ClaudeBot</code> (Anthropic), <code>PerplexityBot</code> (Perplexity), and <code>Google-Extended</code> (Gemini, AI Overviews). Each user-agent is documented publicly. If a <code>Disallow: /</code> is set against any of them, you are invisible to that assistant's training or live retrieval pipeline. Most carriers edited <code>robots.txt</code> during an SEO migration years ago and have not revisited it since.
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>Two, your product page format.</strong> Take one of your FAQ pages and one of your prose product descriptions. Paste each, in turn, into ChatGPT. Ask the same question of each. The quality of the two answers is data about how legibly your site renders to a language model. No probe library needed; your own pages are the test set.
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>Three, your citation rate on real queries.</strong> Pick twenty questions a buyer in your market would actually type. Run them, in the local language, against each of the four assistants. Note when you are cited. Note when a competitor is. The ratio is your current AI citation rate for that surface. It is a number you can produce and defend without our help.
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>Four, your policy wording.</strong> When a buyer asks "am I covered for flooding," the model does not paste your policy. It composes a sentence from it. If your wording is precise, the composition is likely to be accurate. If it is ambiguous, the model fills the gap. The test is the same as step two: paste a sample of your policy, ask a question about it, read the answer.
        </p>

        <h2>What is verifiable today, and what is not.</h2>

        <p>
          The user-agent identities, the robots.txt conformance, and the existence of live web retrieval on each assistant are all public. The exact ranking logic each assistant uses to pick which carrier to name in an answer is not. Nobody has a public list of what is in GPT-5's training data, or how Perplexity weighs freshness against authority, or how Claude decides to refuse a price quote. That is the part the weekly newsletter tries to track through repeated observation.
        </p>

        <h2>Sources.</h2>

        <ul class="sources">
          <li>OpenAI &mdash; GPTBot and related crawlers: <a href="https://platform.openai.com/docs/gptbot" target="_blank" rel="noopener">platform.openai.com/docs/gptbot</a></li>
          <li>Anthropic &mdash; ClaudeBot crawler documentation: <a href="https://support.anthropic.com/en/articles/8896518-does-anthropic-crawl-data-from-the-web-and-how-can-site-owners-block-the-crawler" target="_blank" rel="noopener">support.anthropic.com</a></li>
          <li>Perplexity &mdash; crawler user-agents: <a href="https://www.perplexity.ai/help-center/en/articles/10163415-perplexity-crawlers-user-agents" target="_blank" rel="noopener">perplexity.ai/help-center</a></li>
          <li>Google &mdash; Google-Extended and crawler overview: <a href="https://developers.google.com/search/docs/crawling-indexing/overview-google-crawlers" target="_blank" rel="noopener">developers.google.com/search</a></li>
        </ul>

        <p class="meta-note">
          This page is kept deliberately short and anchored in public sources. The observations, comparisons, and counterexamples that would make a real analysis are in the weekly newsletter, where they belong.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="subscribe" class="subscribe-strip">
      <div class="wrap wrap-article">
        <div class="section-label">Phidea Weekly</div>
        <h3>The part this page does not cover.</h3>
        <p>
          What each assistant actually prefers in practice, how citation rates shift as models retrain, where regulators are starting to treat AI-assistant presence as distribution activity. Once a week, in writing, for people who already know the rest.
        </p>
        <form action="https://buttondown.email/api/emails/embed-subscribe/phidea" method="POST" class="signup">
          <input type="hidden" name="tag" value="ai-visibility" />
          <input type="email" name="email" placeholder="Your email" required />
          <button type="submit">Subscribe →</button>
        </form>
        <p class="signup-small">One email per week. Unsubscribe in one click.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </article>

  <Footer />
</Layout>

<style>
  .wrap-article { max-width: 680px; padding-left: 24px; padding-right: 24px; margin: 0 auto; }

  .article-head { padding: 72px 0 32px; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--line); }
  .article-meta {
    font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
    font-size: 12px;
    color: var(--muted);
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    margin-bottom: 24px;
    display: flex;
    gap: 20px;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }
  .article-head h1 {
    font-family: 'Fraunces', Georgia, serif;
    font-size: 44px;
    line-height: 1.12;
    letter-spacing: -0.015em;
    margin: 0 0 24px;
    font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--ink);
  }
  .standfirst {
    font-size: 20px;
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: var(--ink-2);
    margin: 0;
    font-style: italic;
  }

  .article-body { padding: 48px 0 64px; }
  .article-body p {
    font-size: 18px;
    line-height: 1.72;
    color: var(--ink-2);
    margin: 0 0 24px;
    font-family: 'Fraunces', Georgia, serif;
    font-weight: 400;
  }
  .article-body p strong { color: var(--ink); font-weight: 600; }
  .article-body h2 {
    font-family: 'Fraunces', Georgia, serif;
    font-size: 26px;
    line-height: 1.25;
    font-weight: 500;
    margin: 40px 0 16px;
    color: var(--ink);
  }
  .article-body code {
    font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
    font-size: 0.88em;
    background: var(--soft);
    padding: 1px 6px;
    border-radius: 4px;
    color: var(--ink);
  }
  .sources { list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0 0 32px; }
  .sources li {
    padding: 12px 0;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--line);
    font-size: 15px;
    font-family: 'Inter', sans-serif;
    color: var(--ink-2);
    line-height: 1.55;
  }
  .sources li:last-child { border-bottom: none; }
  .sources a {
    color: var(--accent);
    text-decoration: none;
  }
  .sources a:hover { text-decoration: underline; }
  .meta-note {
    font-size: 14px;
    color: var(--muted);
    font-style: italic;
    line-height: 1.55;
    font-family: 'Inter', sans-serif !important;
  }

  .section-label {
    font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
    font-size: 12px;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    color: var(--accent);
    margin-bottom: 16px;
  }
  .subscribe-strip {
    padding: 72px 0;
    background: var(--soft);
    border-top: 1px solid var(--line);
  }
  .subscribe-strip h3 {
    font-family: 'Fraunces', Georgia, serif;
    font-size: 28px;
    line-height: 1.2;
    margin: 0 0 12px;
    font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--ink);
  }
  .subscribe-strip p {
    font-size: 16px;
    color: var(--ink-2);
    margin: 0 0 24px;
    font-family: inherit;
  }
  .signup { display: flex; gap: 10px; max-width: 520px; }
  .signup input[type=email] {
    flex: 1;
    padding: 14px 16px;
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    border-radius: 10px;
    font-size: 15px;
    font-family: inherit;
    background: var(--bg);
    color: var(--ink);
  }
  .signup button {
    padding: 14px 24px;
    border: none;
    background: var(--ink);
    color: var(--bg);
    border-radius: 10px;
    font-weight: 500;
    cursor: pointer;
    font-size: 15px;
    font-family: inherit;
  }
  .signup button:hover { background: var(--accent); }
  .signup-small { font-size: 13px; color: var(--muted); margin-top: 12px; }

  @media (max-width: 720px) {
    .article-head h1 { font-size: 30px; }
    .standfirst { font-size: 17px; }
    .article-body p { font-size: 17px; }
    .article-body h2 { font-size: 22px; }
    .signup { flex-direction: column; }
  }
</style>
